## R — Rules Reference

### R-1. Citing Rules

**R-1-1.** When implementing or modifying game engine logic, identify the specific rule(s) from `docs/rules/rule_comprehensive.md` that govern the behavior.

**R-1-2.** Include the rule reference (e.g., `§7-1-4-1-1-1`) in code comments for non-obvious logic. Do not add comments for self-evident behavior.

**R-1-3.** Include the rule reference in the commit message when the change is a rules-compliance fix (per G-2-3).

### R-2. Finding the Right Rules

**R-2-1.** To find which rules govern a game concept, consult `docs/rules/RULE-INDEX.md` first. It maps concepts (damage, blocker, K.O., etc.) to specific rule numbers. Read the index instead of scanning the full 1,041-line comprehensive rules file.

**R-2-2.** After identifying the rule numbers, read only the relevant sections from `docs/rules/rule_comprehensive.md`.

**R-2-3.** To check whether a rule is already implemented in the engine, consult `docs/game-engine/RULES-TO-ENGINE-MAP.md`. It tags each rule as **IMPL**, **STUB**, or **GAP** with the corresponding engine file and function.

**R-2-4.** After implementing a gap or fixing a bug, update the corresponding entry in `RULES-TO-ENGINE-MAP.md` in the same commit (per G-1-5).

### R-3. Ambiguity

**R-3-1.** If a rule is ambiguous or two rules appear to conflict, ask for clarification before implementing. Do not silently choose an interpretation.

**R-3-2.** If the comprehensive rules do not address a specific scenario, note this as a gap and flag it to the user.

### R-4. Card Text vs Rules

**R-4-1.** Per §1-3-1, card text takes precedence over the comprehensive rules when they conflict. If an effect implementation contradicts a base rule, cite the card text as the authority.
